##Basic data Manipulations##

#%in% is an infix operator.

# sequence of numbers 1:
a <- seq(1, 5)
# sequence of numbers 2:
b <- seq(3, 12)

# using the %in% operator to check matching values in the vectors
a %in% b
## [1] FALSE FALSE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE
x <- LETTERS[5:10]
y <- LETTERS[2:7]
y %in% x
## [1] FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE
## Check if any value from vector present in another vector
x <- 1:10
y <- 5:20
any(x %in% y)
## [1] TRUE
# Check if all values from vector present in another vector
x <- 1:5
y <- 1:20
all(x %in% y)
## [1] TRUE
# Check values from one vector present in another vector
# Return Index 
a <- c('A','B','C','D','E')
b <- c('C','D')
which(a %in% b)
## [1] 3 4
# Create emp Data Frame
df=data.frame(
  emp_id=c(1,2,3),
  name=c("Smith","Rose","Williams"),
  dept_id=c(10,20,10)
)
df
##   emp_id     name dept_id
## 1      1    Smith      10
## 2      2     Rose      20
## 3      3 Williams      10
# Filter DataFrame
df2 <- df[df$name %in% c('Rose'), ]
df2
##   emp_id name dept_id
## 2      2 Rose      20
# Filter by multiple values
df2 <- df[df$name %in% c('Smith','Rose'), ]
df2
##   emp_id  name dept_id
## 1      1 Smith      10
## 2      2  Rose      20
# Using %in% with if_else
# Create new column
library(dplyr)
df$dept_state <- if_else(df$dept_id %in% c(10,50),'NY','CA')
df
##   emp_id     name dept_id dept_state
## 1      1    Smith      10         NY
## 2      2     Rose      20         CA
## 3      3 Williams      10         NY
'Smith' %in% df$name
## [1] TRUE
# to check if any value in column name is Smith or Rose
df$name %in% c('Smith','Rose')
## [1]  TRUE  TRUE FALSE
# Select columns using %in% operator
df[ ,(names(df) %in% "emp_id")]
## [1] 1 2 3
df[ ,(names(df) %in% c("emp_id", 'name'))]
##   emp_id     name
## 1      1    Smith
## 2      2     Rose
## 3      3 Williams
df %>% select_if(names(.) %in% c('emp_id', 'name'))
##   emp_id     name
## 1      1    Smith
## 2      2     Rose
## 3      3 Williams
# Drop column using %in% operator
df[, !(colnames(df) %in% c("emp_id"))]
##       name dept_id dept_state
## 1    Smith      10         NY
## 2     Rose      20         CA
## 3 Williams      10         NY

67 %in% c(2,5,8,23,67,34)

vec2 <- c(1,2,8,34) 
vec2 %in% vec1
## [1] FALSE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE
vec1[vec2 %in% vec1]
## [1]  5  8 23 34
vec2[vec2 %in% vec1]
## [1]  2  8 34

#https://sparkbyexamples.com/r-programming/replace-column-value-with-another-column-in-r/

# shorter vector:
a <- seq(12, 19)
# longer vector:
b <- seq(1, 16)

# test if elements in longer vector is in shorter:
b %in% a

## [13]  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE

##use which

which (b %in% a)
## [1] 12 13 14 15 16
# Using the operator together with the which() function
which(seq(1, 10) %in% seq(4, 12))
## [1]  4  5  6  7  8  9 10
g <-  c("C", "D", "E")

h <- c("A", "E", "B", "C", "D", "E", "A", "B", "C", "D", "E")

which(h %in% g)

Filtering

  1. Filter for year 2015.

  2. Filter for all names that have a capital letter “B”. Help: take a look at “str_detect()”.

  3. Filter for male names.

  4. Take only names into account which have more than 100 observations.

  5. Show the Top 10 in decreasing order.

  6. Keep only the columns “name” and “prop”

babynames %>% 
  filter (year == 2015) %>% 
  filter(str_detect(name, "B")) %>% 
  filter(sex == "M") %>% 
  filter (n >= 100) %>% 
  arrange(desc(n)) %>% 
  top_n(10) %>% 
  select(name, prop)

  • Calculate the average sales for city and year and save it in object “tx_city_year”.
tx_city_year <- txhousing %>% 
  group_by(city, year) %>% 
  summarise(mean_sales = mean(sales, na.rm = T))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'city'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
ggplot(tx_city_year, aes(x = year, y = mean_sales, col = city)) + 
  geom_line() + 
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Mean Sales", title = "Average Sales per Year and City")
